    <main
    id="tribute-info">
      <h3>A timeline of Ernest Hemingway's adventurous life:</3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1899</strong> - Hemingway is born in Oak Park, Illinois and started writing in a newspaper office at 17.</li>
        <li><strong>1918</strong> - Hemingway joined the Red Cross, first going to Paris, then Milan.</li>
        <li><strong>1925</strong> - 'In Our Time' a collection of short stories, is published.</li>
        <li><strong>1928</strong> - Ernest Hemingway moves to Key West.</li>
        <li><strong>1929</strong> - 'A Farewell To Arms' is published and becomes critically acclaimed.</li>
        <li><strong>1933</strong> - Ernest Hemingway travels to Africa, hunting and gathering material for furture writing.</li>
        <li><strong>1940</strong> - 'For Whom The Bell Tolls' is published and sells over 500,000 copies in six months.</li>
        <li><strong>1952</strong> - 'Old Man and the Sea' is published and sells over 5 million copies almost overnight.</li>
        <li><strong>1953</strong> - Ernest Hemingway wins the Pulitzer Prize for Literature for Old Man and the Sea.</li>
        <li><strong>1954</strong> - Ernest Hemingway wins the Nobel Prize for Literature for Old Man and the Sea.</li>
        <li><strong>1960</strong> - Ernest Hemingway moves to Idaho.</li>
        <li><strong>1961</strong> - Ernest Hemingway commits suicide after battling with depression and paranoia.</li>
   </ul>

<figure>
    <p><em>"â€œIn order to write about life first you must live it."</em></p>
    <figcaption><em>-- Ernest Hemingway</em></figcaption>
</figure>
<p class="disclaimer"><small>*Timeline details courtesy of <a href="https://worldhistoryproject.org/topics/ernest-hemingway/">World History Project</a></small>.</p>
